MLB CAREER LONGEVITY
PREDICTOR
Avery Bishop · Distributed Systems for
Data Science
New College of Florida · Spring 2026
1 · PREDICTION QUESTION
Given an MLB position player's season-level performance statistics and cumulative injury history, how many
years does that player have remaining in their professional career?
2 · DATA SOURCE
The dataset was constructed from Lahman's Baseball Database and MLB injury records as part of a prior
undergraduate thesis on career survival analysis. It contains 63,956 player-season rows spanning MLB
position players from 1871 through 2024, with 44 features covering batting performance (wOBA, PA, hits, home
runs), injury metrics (total injuries, average severity, missed seasons), and derived career aggregates. The
dataset is a one-time static load — ingested into AWS S3 as the bronze layer and not refreshed automatically.
3 · PIPELINE ARCHITECTURE
Stage Service Description
Bronze AWS S3 Raw CSV stored in S3 object store
Ingest GitHub → Databricks PySpark reads raw CSV into Spark DataFrame
Silver Databricks PySpark Cleaned, typed, validated; nulls dropped
Gold Databricks PySpark Feature table exported; model trained here
ML Training MLflow + scikit-learn Random Forest tracked in MLflow registry
Artifact AWS S3 model.pkl + gold CSV uploaded to S3
Serving FastAPI on AWS EC2 Loads model from S3; REST prediction API
UI Streamlit Cloud Public app; calls EC2 endpoint for results
4 · MODEL APPROACH
A Random Forest Regressor (100 estimators, max depth 10, random state 42) was trained on the gold feature
table using scikit-learn and tracked in Databricks MLflow. Twelve features were used: age, wOBA, lagged
wOBA, lagged plate appearances, career plate appearances, career games, years in league, injuries this
season, average injury severity, career injuries, career severity, and missed previous year. The target variable
is years_left — the number of seasons a player continued after a given season. The model was evaluated on a
held-out 20% test set, achieving a Mean Absolute Error of 2.53 years and an R² of 0.363. These metrics
reflect the inherent unpredictability of career length but represent a meaningful signal above baseline for
front-office decision support.
5 · WHAT I LEARNED
The hardest part of this project was not the modeling — it was the infrastructure. Databricks Community Edition
imposed significant restrictions that were not apparent until mid-build: S3 direct mounting, DBFS writes, and
Delta Lake persistence were all blocked, forcing creative workarounds at each stage. The Lambda serving layer
was abandoned entirely after cross-platform packaging failures (Windows-compiled numpy binaries are
incompatible with Lambda's Linux runtime), and replaced with a FastAPI server on EC2. If rebuilding, I would
start with a full-tier Databricks trial to avoid the Community Edition ceiling, use Docker from the start for
reproducible packaging, and allocate more time to feature engineering — particularly position-specific aging
curves and park factor adjustments — which would likely improve model performance meaningfully beyond the
current R² of 0.363.
